    "summary": "The Iroquois Confederacy (Haudenosaunee, 'People of the Longhouse'), traditionally founded between the 12th and 15th centuries, was one of the most sophisticated political confederacies in pre-Columbian North America, uniting five (later six) Iroquoian-speaking nations — the Mohawk, Oneida, Onondaga, Cayuga, and Seneca (later joined by the Tuscarora) — under a constitutional framework known as the Great Law of Peace (Gayanashagowa) attributed to the prophet Deganawida and his spokesman Hiawatha. The confederacy occupied the Finger Lakes region and the Mohawk Valley of present-day New York State.\n\nThe Great Law of Peace established a representative council of fifty chiefs (sachems) with elaborate procedures for deliberation, consensus-building, and peaceful resolution of disputes between member nations — a genuine constitutional government based on representative principles. Some historians and several of America's founders (including Benjamin Franklin, who attended an Iroquois conference in 1744 and explicitly praised the confederacy's governmental system) have argued that the Iroquois Confederacy influenced the thinking behind the Articles of Confederation and the United States Constitution, though the extent of direct influence remains debated. The Haudenosaunee became the dominant military power of the northeastern woodlands, controlling access to beaver fur trade routes that made their alliance crucial to both French and English colonial powers in the 17th–18th centuries. The confederacy was split by the American Revolution, with most nations supporting Britain; the subsequent American victory resulted in the dispossession of Iroquois lands and the dispersal of the confederacy.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iroquois",
